abstract: >
  This paper formalizes an epistemic limitation of observational evaluation: some failures
  under intervention are undetectable from observation alone, even when predictive accuracy
  at the model interface is perfect. The core diagnostic is the unfaithful cut, a reduction
  induced by a modelâ€™s representational interface that is closed under prediction but not
  closed under admissible interventions. When distinct trajectories (histories) are collapsed
  into a single interface state, observational adequacy can be preserved while intervention
  behavior becomes underdetermined: admissible actions may separate histories the interface
  treats as equivalent, yielding counterfactual ambiguity that cannot be resolved by additional
  observational data or improved prediction alone. The framework is consistent with causal
  insufficiency (from a causal inference perspective) while emphasizing how insufficiency can
  arise from representational interface design in learned systems where causal structure is
  implicit. The paper provides formal definitions, a diagnostic test, and worked illustrative
  examples including a tractable finite special case and a minimal offline-RL-style setting.


